\paperw12240\paperh15840\margl1800\margr1800\margt1440\margb1440\f0\fs24\cf0
\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Every artist who has ever tried to capture the beauty of nature has failed. Why they even try is a mystery. The don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t seem to understand that beauty is out there in the world, and it\u8217\'92s connected to everything else. To capture it, one would have to capture everything, and that\u8217\'92s not possible. It is also morally wrong.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri burped.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He took another swig of the burgeon hooch that he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d left steeping in a hole in the ground. This hole was exactly halfway between Vigram\u8217\'92s rich leech farm, and his own failed bean farm. He had a few hidey holes like this, spread out along the way. He\u8217\'92d sip one hole\u8217\'92s hooch, and by the time he was finished, he\u8217\'92d arrived at the next.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He took another swig, then continued walking. He took a longer swig, then continued spiraling over the fact that he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d ever picked up a paintbrush.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Because what is a painting, really? Paint a tree, and all those leaves get reduced to flecks of green. A living leaf with all its complexity, its pattern, its anastomosing veins pumped full of vital fluids, its green birth and brown death, its fall from the branch, its decay into dirt, that whole nested universe, that complexity, reduced to a fleck of green. Reduced, because art is seduction. It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s about looking at }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 this}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 , and explicitly }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 not}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 that}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 . Paint an oasis, and look, there\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s a naked woman bathing in the mossy water. Focus the viewer\u8217\'92s gaze by sharpening the droplets of jade that gleam on her cinnamon skin. The leaf? Feather its edge into the sky. Blame it on the effects of atmospheric haze. Perhaps bend the leaf around if it doesn\u8217\'92t slide a wandering eye down towards that temptress\u8217\'92 stare. Consider removing the tree entirely, because it\u8217\'92s good practice to erase all evidence of a crime.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Perhaps it was too much to call it a crime.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A tantrum was more like it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Yes, a painting was nothing but a look-at-me tantrum thrown by a spoiled child. Only the brattiest, most self-absorbed child could see the wonder of creation and say, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93People ought to know about }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 my}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  interpretation.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 As if creation could not speak for itself. And somehow, these tantrums are indulged. Crowds of enablers herd themselves indoors to speed through even the quaintest art gallery. Reality is right outside, but they\u8217\'92d rather see it cornered, killed, flayed, then put on display, with choice sections of its hide stitched into pretty frames.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 But, Mandri understood. People wanted to know where they should look. Might as well frame something for them, then charge a fee. A shame it all required the pretension that something important was happening, because he would have liked being rich.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Go and paint all this,\u8221\'94 Mandri said, sweeping his arm over the world. \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s not possible. Take as long as you like. Take a lifetime. Take ten lifetimes! Then\u8230\'85 and then\u8230\'85\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 And then he forgot what he was on about because he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d rambled onto his farm. It was the ugliest spot of land in all the world.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 His field, more of a dust patch, was impaled with so many unproductive bean poles that it looked a bit like a gentle hill had picked a fight with a porcupine. Some of those poles were wrapped with withered beanstalks, looking like martyred pilgrims. And there shallow pits all over, divots, each stained with an irregular ring of salt.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri took a massive swig of his burgeon hooch.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The hooch made those salt stains come alive.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Even now, they wiggled and sparkled, like swarms of white larvae. They crawled and gnawed on those wilted bean stalks, making it seem like he hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t lost a battle to an inanimate thing. That was a pestilential swarm sent by demons.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He wished he was sipping on black-eye burgeons. The effect of these down-valley burgeons was a little more muted. They\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d make textures slide, edges bleed, but their chief effect was that anything bright would sparkle\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the salt, the mountainous puffs of cloud overhead, the rays of sun that filtered through them, pretty much everything that wasn\u8217\'92t hidden in shadow would sparkle. The effect was even less pronounced when the burgeon was mixed in with a nasty hooch like this, but that didn\u8217\'92t much matter. The goal was to relax and waste the day away in the shade of his solitary hornscrub tree.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 That tree was the only thing on his farm that he appreciated. If he were to paint a painting, he would paint that tree. There was his shack, but that more of a lean-to against a fence. There was also an ox. A yellow-headed ox stood amongst the bean poles. At least twenty big leeches were suckered onto its side.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Would you look at that,\u8221\'94 Mandri mused.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It was the same damn ox from Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s leech farm. The same short haired yellow head, the same shaven body, save for the lower legs. There were red marks in its armpits where wooden bars propped it up in the leech lake, keeping it from collapsing into the murk from sheer exhaustion. Even from this distance, Mandri could see little red circles where leeches had fallen off.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s heart turned for the beast. It was completely out of place and obviously unable to care for itself. It was liable to die. And now it was loping towards him, as if to ask for directions.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mruuuuu,\u8221\'94 it said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I can\u8217\'92t do anything for you,\u8221\'94 Mandri shouted, but even as he spoke, he knew it wasn\u8217\'92t true. He could do something. He could scrape off those leeches. He could lead the beast to water. He could go to the extreme and devote the rest of his empty life to caring for that ox. He wasn\u8217\'92t going to do that, but he could! He wasn\u8217\'92t going to, because this was an ox. Thousands of oxes just like it were being butchered and eaten throughout the world. He\u8217\'92d eaten plenty of beef himself. It would almost be hypocritical to help it. Vigram had a whole leech farm full of animals that needed saving, and he hadn\u8217\'92t spared one thought for helping any of them. Were they somehow less worthy? Was he somehow responsible for all of them? Where was the line?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The ox mooed again as it sauntered close.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Damn,\u8221\'94 Mandri muttered.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The beast really needed help. But, so did he. That was the way of the world. The only way it worked was if creatures took care of themselves, and even then, it didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t work very well.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He sipped his hooch.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The short hairs on the ox\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s head were swirling. He sipped his hooch again and downed the dregs. He had more hooch sitting inside his hornscrub tree and wanted it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Can\u8217\'92t do anything for you,\u8221\'94 he said, absolutely disgusted with himself.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He made for the tree, and the ox followed him. When he sat down in the tree\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s shade, the ox did too, ribs squishing leeches.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do we know each other, or something?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The ox stared at him with that bovine dumbness. Its big, dozing breaths rolled its bare hide back and forth over his sagging spine. Now that Mandri was positively high on burgeons, the sight of that rolling hide was a sight to see. The skin appeared to boil.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He found his hooch in its hidey hole and took a big, big sip. He remembered to store the burgeons he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d bought from Geem, and then he settled in to watch the world boil.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Ox snorts}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 What the hell?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Sees a woman wrapped in black  approaching. Other side of his fence, making for the gap. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ah shit,\u8221\'94 Mandri moaned. Though the figures were blurry, edges bleeding, He wasn\u8217\'92t too far gone yet to realize who it was: Lora.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \tx1123\tx1685\tx2246\tx2794\tx3355\tx3917\tx4478\tx5040\tx5602\tx6163\tx6725\fi720\ri-720\sl288\slmult1\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri!\u8221\'94 The biggest shape shouted. \u8220\'93What are the chances!?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Go away,\u8221\'94 Mandri muttered.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lora doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t go away. Comes towards him. Wrapped in black like }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She moved without making a sound, for she wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t adorned with the usual veneer of civilization; no shine-silver bracelets, or bangles, or gold hoop earrings, no makeup or red-thread leaves trimming her robe. The only ornament on her entire body was the turtle-shell hilt of a dagger which she kept fashionably crooked in her waistband. The rest of her tawny self could have been slapped together in a reed hut on the banks of the river Jek; robes black, but stained dusty brown all over. She was dirty, with perfect teeth. A full complement of perfectly straight and sun-bleached teeth were sparkling inside her boiling blur. They practically outshone the sun.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lora was standing over him. a blot of a person amidst a sparkling, burgeon addled world. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s instinct was to drink as much of his jumped-up hooch as he could, because no doubt Lora would try to snatch it. Then again, she might not know what it was. It looked like milk. And it would be a waste to drink it all in one go.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Wasting it wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t do.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 This was a special drink.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Worthy of preservation.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri had made plenty of special drinks, but this one was extra special because it was right here, a thing of the present. He could maybe try to hide it, tuck the clay jug away somewhere, maybe just nudge it behind the tree, but no doubt that vixen\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes were\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re drooling,\u8221\'94 Lora said disdainfully. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Burgeons can make a mess of a person, but Mandri knew he wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t so far gone yet. A peculiar thing about this particular brew was that it left his wits untouched. Well, mostly untouched. Maybe a little touched, it was difficult to gauge. Lora\u8217\'92s hair might be flowing out of her cowl like some perpetual waterfall, but in Mandri\u8217\'92s view this did not qualify as a sign of lost wits.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I have big plans for you,\u8221\'94 Lora said. Her teeth flashed as he spoke. Her head pitched into a suspecting tilt.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Lora,\u8221\'94 Mandri said forcefully, trying to sound sober, \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m not going to kiss you. I\u8217\'92ve made my choice.\u8221\'94 He took another big swig of his hooch to emphasize it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh,\u8221\'94 Lora said, chuckling. \u8220\'93Is that what you think I\u8217\'92m here for? You have misjudged me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  Then again, he couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t really trust his own interpretations of things at the moment. Even the basic awareness of how many people were present was slipping, because it took all the way until now for him to notice that Vigram was here too, standing some yards away, scalp-sweating in the sun like a dutiful servant. He was staring at Mandri like he was planning to use Mandri\u8217\'92s bones for something.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why\u8217\'92s he looking at me like that? Is it the ox?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lora unfolded a short stool from nowhere, then sat down uncomfortably close. She didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t ask if Mandri minded. \u8220\'93I will lead with this,\u8221\'94 she said as she crossed her legs and leaned forward. \u8220\'93I am not Vigram\u8217\'92s daughter.\u8221\'94 She thumb-pointed to Vigram over her shoulder. \u8220\'93He and I are not related in any way. He\u8217\'92s a bit of a mule. I know that is a lot to stomach, I know. We will come back to it. First, drink up. The burgeon bush is a blessed provision from the gods.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93How do you\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Drink!\u8221\'94 Lora demanded. \u8220\'93Do not think. Drink, and simply be. It may help to pretend that I am a stranger. It would be unstrangerly for me to insert myself into your decision to obliterate yourself. I am here only to observe.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s skin prickled. He clutched his jug of hooch close because if Lora was after something, there was only one thing she could take.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I am here,\u8221\'94 Lora said, \u8220\'93because you passed a test. You spurned me, beautiful as I am, and you rejected the easy life Vigram offered. Everyone else might look at you and see a dumb, hopeless young man, but\u8230\'85well, I see that too, but I also see in you something special. You are fertile ground, Mandri. Fate has forced you off the easy road. It\u8217\'92s also saved your life. You have potential.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \tx1123\tx1685\tx2246\tx2794\tx3355\tx3917\tx4478\tx5040\tx5602\tx6163\tx6725\fi720\ri-720\sl288\slmult1\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Lora,\u8221\'94 Mandri said, \u8220\'93what in god\u8217\'92s name are you on about?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lora\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s shoulders fell, but this was not discouragement, for her smiling eyes went wide. \u8220\'93I will tell you a story,\u8221\'94 she said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Please don\u8217\'92t.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why not? Good stories are a kind of currency in this world. They make people do things they wouldn\u8217\'92t otherwise think to do. In a way, the right story, applied to the right person, it buys them. The listener becomes what the storyteller wants them to be. Ask yourself what it is I want you to be as I tell you my story. Well, it\u8217\'92s not }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 my}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  story, it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s a story about a wastrel. You know him.\u8221\'94 Her lips pinched into a wry grin, as if she\u8217\'92d just insulted Mandri and didn\u8217\'92t want to get away with it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Maybe I do,\u8221\'94 Mandri said flatly.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, I\u8217\'92m sure that you do. You see, this wastrel, he was a\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri cut Lora short with a snort, then settled into the tree like he was about to go in for a nap. He couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 really}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  settle in, because he knew his face might be doing things all on its own. That was another thing about burgeons, they numbed the face, so he was never quite sure what it was doing. He could be making kissy lips at Lora right now and he wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t know it unless he focused.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri, this is Vigram\u8217\'92s story,\u8221\'94 Lora said. \u8220\'93His }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 true}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  story. He never told you he was just like you, useless, but he was. He was almost exactly as you are now. He stole his father\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s money, the money meant to bring him up in this world, and he spent it on burgeons, women, and people who he thought were friends. His life\u8217\'92s prospects quickly came to nothing.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri looked to Vigram for some confirmation it was true, because no way in hell Vigram would assent to be talked about like that, even if it was true. But Vigram stayed silent. The man betrayed nothing but the general unease of standing in the heat of the sun.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93When Vigram\u8217\'92s father found out what he had done\u8230\'85I\u8217\'92ll simply say that the man\u8217\'92s anger was profound. I won\u8217\'92t bother you with the details. You won\u8217\'92t comprehend them. How could you? You you don\u8217\'92t have children. What\u8217\'92s important to the story is that Vigram\u8217\'92s father began to believe that this existence is a mistake. Given the rough nature of your current condition you might have some sympathy for the idea. I know this ox does. You can see it in it\u8217\'92s eyes\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 this life lacks purpose. I would go further and say that I can }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 prove}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  that we\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 I speak for every living creature now\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 we have no intrinsic purpose.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri looked to the ox, hoping the beast would voice its opinion. Then he remembered that the ox was only a dumb animal.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri,\u8221\'94 Lora said, regaining Mandri\u8217\'92s attention. \u8220\'93Let me prove it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Prove what?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I can prove that none of us are meant to be in this world.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Her eyes turned to Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s failure of a farm. To the east, the world beyond was drier, more thorny, and it was like that all the way up to the Hias mountains. Depressingly, the other side of those mountains was a desert.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If a person ever finds themselves blessed with wealth and health beyond comprehension, what happens to them? I suspect you have seen it first hand, how impoverishing wealth is when a person acquires it. I\u8217\'92ve seen it through the eyes of the Hrkan Lords. Without any real concerns to distract them, you might think that they are free to pursue their life\u8217\'92s intrinsic purpose and be fulfilled, but that is not what happens. They either lose themselves to pleasure, or they begin to invent enemies where there are none. They feel boxed in. It is a frustration so thorough and complete that they lose all sense. What does it mean when wealth frees these people from the indignities of life, and they turn, naturally, into some aberrant husk of a person? Do you know?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Who are you?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You do see the implication, yes?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s vision was beginning to swirl, so he could hardly see anything except for the Lora\u8217\'92s brown locks flowing out the front of her cowl. Each curl was like a river unto itself, endlessly flowing, dissolving, yet always staying in the same spot.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri, the implication is that what purpose we do have is }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 crafted.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  It is }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 made.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  It exists outside of yourself, and that means it is something you can lose. I put it to you that losing your purpose is the greatest horror a human being can experience. It happened to Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s father. Don\u8217\'92t laugh, you of all people should know how this can break a person.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t aware that he was laughing.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Vigram was his father\u8217\'92s purpose in life. To borrow a poetic turn, Vigram was his father\u8217\'92s challenge to the Black. Not only did the old man lose that challenge, his attempt was squandered. If Vigram were killed, he could have moved into grief, but no, he had challenged the Black and the Black answered back by turning young Vigram into the living embodiment of a life\u8217\'92s wasted labor. So, the old man sent Vigram a note which said, \u8216\'91You are going to die\u8217\'92.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Won\u8217\'92t we all.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes! Yes, you already see where this is going. Vigram might have been a wastrel, but he did not want to die. He read the note and grew ill. He began to see his father in every shadow. He couldn\u8217\'92t enjoy himself, couldn\u8217\'92t bother the whores, you know, couldn\u8217\'92t sleep in the same place twice. If you knew his father, you\u8217\'92d know what was coming for him. What can I say? Vigram was a wastrel who couldn\u8217\'92t confront even the thought of a confrontation. So what did he do? He ran away to find a witch to fix his problems for him. If a witch could predict the exact moment when his father would kill him, then he could, he hoped, avoid that moment. So, he found a witch. Guess what she did.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93She bored him.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93She showed him what he was.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And what was that?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93A leech.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lora reached over and ripped a leech off straight off the old ox\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s leg. Somehow, the ox didn\u8217\'92t seem to mind.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She held the leech up like  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri sneered at it. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Disgusting creature.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, please,\u8221\'94 Lora chided. \u8220\'93Leeches are the only honest creatures in all of creation. They don\u8217\'92t pretend to be more than what they are, which is a mouth, a stomach, and an anus. }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 You}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  think that you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re a person.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 There was a nasty squint in the shadow of her shawl, and it was fixed on Mandri.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Have you ever killed someone?\u8221\'94 she asked. Her voice was dire. The narrow whites of her eyes seemed possessed of an inner light.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Killing?\u8221\'94 Mandri mumbled. \u8220\'93What is this about?\u8221\'94 He looked to Vigram for reassurance, but the man stood uneasily in his spot. \u8220\'93I guess it depends on who is getting killed,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93Are these, I don\u8217\'92t know, are they murderers?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do not answer my questions with questions.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri reflexively took another drink. As the burgeon hooch trickled down his throat, Lora seemed to grow taller in her seat. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look,\u8221\'94 he said, after licking his lips, \u8220\'93What\u8217\'92s the point of this, anyway? You want me to kill someone?\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Would that be such a terrible a thing?\u8221\'94 Lora asked through a grimace of a smile. \u8220\'93Right this very moment, people are dying. I do not mean one or two, their deaths number in the thousands. Thousands are dying, }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 right this very moment}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 . You don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t think of them, but I do. It is my duty to ensure that they are dying for a purpose.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What do you need me for?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Have you ever prayed to Solraheen?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Who }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 are}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  you?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Have you ever prayed to the good god Solraheen?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Of course I have, who hasn\u8217\'92t?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lora\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s upper lip curled in contempt.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Have you spoken the words yourself?\u8221\'94 she asked. \u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t count prayer circles where someone else does the heavy lifting. Have you ever run away to a quiet place and whispered words to Solraheen?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t answer because the lines of Lora\u8217\'92s hair were fractaling into smoke, and the heat from that smoke appeared to melt Lora\u8217\'92s eyebrows down into her wrinkles. Yes, wrinkles. She was no pert beauty, Lora was a right old witch.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re high as a blackbeak,\u8221\'94 Lora said. \u8220\'93That is good. You are fitting the mold.\u8221\'94 She pulled from her black robe a brown paper booklet whose makeshift spine was composed of peeling wax and fraying twine. She flattened this crudity against her hip. Mandri craned his neck to see if he could read the scrawl on the cover, but of course the burgeonsight made that impossible.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She opened the book, summoned a stick of charcoal from her robe, then jotted a note onto one of the browning pages. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You are untethered, that much is clear. The next test, however, I am not so sure you will succeed. Don\u8217\'92t look so frightened, boy, that also means that I am not sure you will fail. This should excite you. Are you excited, young Mandrameen?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No,\u8221\'94 said Mandri bluntly. \u8220\'93Please leave.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lora laughed. Hers was a grating laugh\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 half cackle, half delirious groan. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That is not how this works,\u8221\'94 she said, cherishing Mandri\u8217\'92s simplicity. \u8220\'93You do not get to decide whether or not you will play a part. If you are fit for divine purpose, then you will make the choice which is to be made, and that is that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She closed her book and tucked it back into her robes. Mandri, thinking she was about to depart, whispered a chime of praise, but this was muted the moment he saw her staring at him. She was holding him in her eyes. Yes, those were a lover\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes, or a murderer\u8217\'92s; it was difficult to say because there was a fine line between the two and the burgeonsight had her irises wiggling and popping like beans in hot oil.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What keeps you here?\u8221\'94 she asked. \u8220\'93You have nothing. Is it the ox?\u8221\'94 She stepped around Mandri\u8217\'92s outstretched legs to give the ox a pat. The beast\u8217\'92s protuberant eyes appeared spellbound. They stared off into the horizon.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No,\u8221\'94 Mandri said simply.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then you won\u8217\'92t mind if I make a meal of him?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Make a what?\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You won\u8217\'92t mind if I butcher and eat this ox?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why would I? It\u8217\'92s not mine.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do you not recognize that this ox saved your life?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It did?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The ox mooed in recognition. The old witch shook her head as if impressed with Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s ignorance. Then she gripped the turtle-shell hilt at her waist and pulled a long, black knife from an unseen sheathe. The sudden sight of this thin, curved blade drew Mandri up, and when she put it against ox\u8217\'92s neck, he nearly fainted.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why not let him be?\u8221\'94 Mandri pleaded.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The boy fears death,\u8221\'94 Vigram said from his spot in the sun.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93He fears himself,\u8221\'94 Lora said as she coaxed the ox into lifting his head. She scraped her knife\u8217\'92s edge up and down against his throat. The poor beast, eager to get in a good scratch, closed his eyes and lifted his chin as high as he could to make sure she could scratch the whole length of it. \u8220\'93Why would he fear death when he\u8217\'92s the one with an insatiable stomach?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, come on,\u8221\'94 Mandi said, \u8220\'93Why not leave him alone?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Would you hurt me to save this ox?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t think I could. You\u8217\'92re obviously a witch. And Vigram\u8217\'92s right there. I know I\u8217\'92m at your mercy.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, but if you had the power. If you could kill both of us to rescue this poor, suffering creature, would you do it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri opened his mouth to say, immediately, yes! Then he remembered how, moments ago, that ox had sauntered up to him looking for rescue, and he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d did nothing. He couldn\u8217\'92t even bring himself to remove a single leech. He could have tried, could have taken the ox over to\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You see!\u8221\'94 Lora exclaimed as she lowered her blade. \u8220\'93He hesitates.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Stern Vigram stroked his beard. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hesitation could go both ways,\u8221\'94 he said. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes,\u8221\'94 Lora agreed. \u8220\'93Still, I know how to put my finger on the balance.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 With uncanny speed she cupped Gil\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s snout under her arm and reached around his neck with her knife. She plunged her blade into the ox\u8217\'92s flesh, drove it tight up against his jaw, then abruptly yanked it round to the other side.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Gil let out a powerful bellow, deep and pitching. His whole bulk lurched backwards, pulling his head from her grasp. He bucked as he stood up, knocking her aside, and he hoofed it into the dusty field, bleeding and bleating as he went. He came to a stop just twenty yards away, apparently realizing there was nowhere to go. Confused at the betrayal, and weakened by the dreadful spurts of blood pouring out of his neck, he sank to his knees.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri snarled, picked up a rock, and he leaped after the old hag who sat watching with glee.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 One sharp elbow into his uglies sent him sprawling to the ground.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So, you\u8217\'92re not a eunuch,\u8221\'94 Lora said with an awful sneer.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri scrambled to reach for her robe, but the cloth appeared to melt between his fingers. And then he saw something he could not believe.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She flew.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She flew, feet off the dirt, straight like an arrow; she }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 flew}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  towards his dying ox. Every last aspect which once was beautiful faded away to reveal an aged, scowling head, dark eyes alight with bestial rage. The sound of her shriek was borne not from her lungs, but from the deepest depths of Shis.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She plunged head first into Gil\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s body, tearing a hole into his belly as easily as if her nose were made of flint. Gil crumpled to the ground, and she went with him, head and shoulders fixed into his side. And before Gil\u8217\'92s spine had the chance to spasm, she tore herself from his flesh. The neck of his first stomach was clenched between her teeth. She spat it out, then ripped the rest of the innards free from their lining. Kneeling, she hugged the largest stomach up to the sun. Her lips uttered a speech as black as Fabled Black. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri clasped his ears, but he could not look away. He prepared himself for some final gross barbarity, and it came when Lora\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s chanting appeared to squeeze a bright speck of light from Gil\u8217\'92s stomach. She sipped this magnificence into her chest through pursed lips, as one might sip a too-hot tea.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Satiated, she dropped Gil\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s great stomach onto the dirt.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The tension in her shoulders softened. Her face, a withered sponge of blood, smiled at Mandri, and in the next instant, some unseen force appeared to pluck her off the ground and then rip her out of the sky.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Next thing Mandri knew, she had disappeared entirely.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Vigram was standing above him, excited. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93When she leaves like that,\u8221\'94 Vigram said, \u8220\'93it means that what happens next is what she wants to happen. It is a good sign. You are on the path. All you have to do is choose to get up and walk. Walk with me, Mandri. You can bring your drink.\u8221\'94}}